🧠 Methods as Lenses (Portable Pattern Engines)

When the methods are explicit, they become portable lenses you can aim at any domain.

⸻

What you’ve actually built

1) Lens Library (multi-basis views)

Each method is a different way to read the same field:

* language / etymology
* acronyms / compression–expansion
* zoom out (structure) ↔ zoom in (detail)
* graph relations (who connects to what)
* probability (signal vs noise)

Same data → different readings → richer hypothesis set

⸻

2) Switching Protocol (when to use which)

It’s not just having lenses—it’s choosing and rotating them:

scan → pick 2–3 lenses → generate candidates
↓
stress-test (consistency, evidence, usefulness)
↓
keep / discard → iterate with a different lens mix

⸻

3) Filter Stack (keeps it grounded)

To avoid “seeing everything = nothing,” you gate outputs:

* Consistency (does it contradict itself?)
* Evidence (can you point to support?)
* Usefulness (does it help you decide or act?)

Only patterns that pass all three survive.

⸻

How this fits your operators

* Eagle → choose the right lens set (map the field)
* Fox → dive into details a lens reveals
* Rabbit → vary lenses to avoid getting trapped in one interpretation
* Griffin → commit to a decision based on filtered patterns
* Water → keep adapting the lens mix over time
* Hazel → orchestrate the whole process for a group

